page.text: This letter will serve to provide additional information relevant to existing Stratford Road traffic
operations and the potential traffic impact of the 243 Steele Road development on Stratford Road.
As part of the Traffic Impact Study, a turning movement count was conducted in February 2014 at
the intersection of Steele Road at Stratford Road and the McAuley Driveway on a typical weekday
during the highest generating traffic hours of the day (the 7-9AM morning commuter peak hour
and the 4-6PM afternoon commuter peak hour). The counts revealed that the existing morning
peak hour of traffic is 7:15 to 8:15 AM and the afternoon peak hour of traffic is 5:00 to 6:00 PM.
These existing peak hours are concurrent with the anticipated peak hours of the proposed
residential development and were therefore analyzed in the traffic study for impacts.
The counts revealed that six (6) vehicles northbound on Steele Road turned right onto Stratford
Road during the morning peak hour. Intersection counts also recorded that six (6) vehicles turned
right during the afternoon peak hour. Similarly, five (5) vehicles made the left turn from Steele
Road southbound onto Stratford Road during the morning peak hour and seven (7) vehicles made
the left turn during the afternoon peak hour.
This equates to a total of 11 vehicles entering Stratford Road during the morning peak hour and 13
vehicles entering during the afternoon peak hour. These volumes represent an average of
approximately one vehicle every 5 minutes which is not considered abnormal for a low volume

page.text: In addition to the traffic counts collected by Fuss & O’Neill, the Town of West Hartford
conducted 24-hour traffic counts and vehicle speed counts in November 2013 during two separate
weeks using an automatic traffic recorder (machine tube count). The first ATR count was
completed during the week of October 31, 2013 through November 6, 2013 just northeast of Steele
Road. The ATR revealed that the weekday average daily traffic on Stratford Road was 183 vehicles.
The second ATR was placed further north on Stratford Road along the straight away during the
period of November 6, 2014 through November 18, 2014 and recorded a weekday average daily
traffic volume of 158 vehicles. Average weekend traffic volumes were recorded to be 133 vehicles
for the first ATR and 124 vehicles for the second ATR.

page.text: Anticipated trip generation for the 37 residential homes on Stratford Road was calculated using
rates indicated in the Institute of Transportation Engineers (ITE) Trip Generation manual, which is
an industry standard for determining traffic generation for various land uses. The manual indicates
that 37 single-family homes can be expected to generate 9 entering trips during the morning peak
hour of adjacent street traffic and 27 entering trips during the afternoon peak hour. Similarly,
weekday daily trip generation volumes are projected to be 421 vehicles per day. The actual traffic
counts reported above indicate that Stratford Road experiences significantly less traffic in
comparison to what a similarly sized residential development would be expected to generate based
The daily traffic volumes and speeds recorded on Stratford Road are less than what would be
expected for similar low-volume, low-speed residential roadways. The recorded volumes indicate
that the roadway is functioning with a primary purpose to serve its local residents as opposed to
Of the vehicles traveling northbound on Steele Road during the peak hours, 6 of them turn right
onto Stratford Road during both the morning and afternoon peak hours. In comparison, the Steele
Road northbound right turning volume onto Route 44 is significantly higher (153 during the
morning peak hour and 86 during the afternoon peak hour). Therefore, the traffic count data
indicates that the vast majority of northbound Steele Road traffic which is intending on heading
eastbound on Route 44 travels north to the traffic signal at Route 44 and makes a right turn as
opposed to turning onto Stratford Road. Less than 4% of the northbound Steele Road traffic
heading east on Route 44 (6 out of 159 vehicles) used Stratford Road during the morning peak
hour as opposed to using the traffic signal. In addition, this calculation assumes that all six (6) of
the recorded turns onto Stratford Road were cut through trips (not local traffic), which is most
likely not the case. These recorded traffic volumes indicate that the volume of any cut through
traffic on Stratford Road is minimal (less than six vehicles) during the peak hours.
The presence of a “No Through Traffic” sign at the start of Stratford Road reinforces to drivers
that this route is a local roadway and driver compliance with this sign is high as evidenced by the
traffic count data. It should be noted that violation of this sign could result in a ticket if enforced by
It should be noted that traffic generation from the existing McAuley development is already
included in the traffic counts collected by the Traffic Impact Study and is therefore included as part
of the Background and Combined Conditions analysis conducted in the study. The traffic counts
collected during this study revealed that 33 vehicles entered the site driveway on Steele Road during
the morning peak hour and 7 exited. During the afternoon peak hour, 15 vehicles entered and 26
exited. Capacity analysis indicates that the intersection of Steele Road at the McAuley driveway and
Stratford Road operates efficiently during the peak hours with Level of Service (LOS) B operations
for traffic exiting McAuley and LOS A operations for traffic turning into McAuley and Stratford
Road. These LOS indicate that vehicles experience minimal delays at this intersection both before
and after the inclusion of the proposed development traffic.

text.b: Development Trip Generation, Trip Distribution, and Cut Through Potential

page.text: The Traffic Impact Study summarizes the anticipated trip generation for the proposed residential
development. Trip generation estimates for the 200 apartments are based on rates provided in the
industry standard ITE Trip Generation manual. Rates in this manual are calculated based on actual
counts collected at similar apartment complexes across the country. For the 243 Steele Road
development, ITE indicates the apartments will generate 20 new entering trips in the morning peak
hour and 82 exiting trips. During the afternoon peak hour, 83 new vehicle trips will be generated
entering the site and 45 will exit.
When determining where traffic generated by the development will go, the traffic study utilizes
existing traffic volume distributions on Steele Road and its intersections with Stratford Road, Route
44, and Asylum Street. Specifically, it is estimated that 25% of the traffic will exit the site, head
north on Steele Road, and then turn east on Route 44. This equates to 21 vehicle trips in the
morning peak hour. As previously mentioned, in the existing condition, there are six (6) right turns
from Steele Road northbound that turn right onto Stratford Road and 153 northbound right turns
from Steele Road onto Route 44. Thus, less than 4% of the traffic heading to Route 44 eastbound
is using Stratford Road in the existing condition, and this assumes that 100% of the Stratford Road
traffic is cut through, which is highly conservative. Using this same distribution (4%) with the site
generated traffic heading north on Steele Road and then right onto Route 44 (21 vehicles), we
calculate that 0.8 vehicles (or 0 to 1 vehicle) would leave the site and use Stratford Road in the
morning peak hour. Thus, the volume of traffic that would be generated by the development and
ultimately use Stratford Road would be negligible.
Fuss & O’Neill staff conducted a formal travel time study during the week of June 2, 2014 during
the morning peak and off peak hours as well as the afternoon peak hours to confirm the average
travel times between the Steele Road/Stratford Road intersection and the Route 44/Whetten Road
intersection along both the Steele Road and Stratford Road routes. Ten travel time runs for each
period were completed along each route and averaged.
The study revealed that the average travel times during the morning study period along the two
routes were identical at 1 minute, 13 seconds. During the afternoon peak period, the travel times
along Stratford Road were longer (1 minute and 7 seconds vs. 1 minute and 1 second taking the
primary route along Steele Road). There was no observed time savings for vehicles taking Stratford
Road when averaged out over several runs. It was observed that whether the traffic signal at Steele
Road was green or red, assuming there were no cars were waiting in the queue, then traveling the
primary route up Steele Road was consistently quicker. If the light at Steele Road was red and a
queue was present that restricted right turn on red traffic, then the Stratford Road route was
During the majority of the travel time runs it was observed that vehicles attempting to turn right
from Steele Road northbound onto Route 44 eastbound were not obstructed by a queue at the
traffic signal. In more instances, drivers taking the Steele Road route benefitted from the traffic
signal. Conversely, significant delay was observed for vehicles originating on Stratford Road and
attempting to find a suitable gap when turning from Whetten Road onto Route 44, especially
In summary, travel time observations revealed, on average, no travel time savings by cutting
through Stratford Road to access Route 44 eastbound from Steele Road. Several factors combine
to make Stratford Road an undesirable cut through route: the low-volume, low-speed residential
nature of Stratford Road, the traffic calming improvements installed at the south end, the awkward
intersection alignment with Whetten Road at the north end, and the difficulty for vehicles to make
a right turn from Whetten Road onto Route 44 without the aid of a traffic signal granting right-of-
way. In general, potential “cut through” routes that do not offer a noticeable, significant travel
time savings are typically undesirable to drivers as they quickly learn that the primary route is
During construction of the proposed 243 Steele Road residential development, construction
vehicles will be directed to enter and exit the site from the south on Steele Road (via Asylum
Avenue). Construction vehicles will enter the south driveway of the existing loop road on the site.
Under this circulation, construction traffic will not pass Stratford Road or impact traffic operations
at the intersection of Steele Road at Stratford Road.
Fuss & O’Neill has reviewed the May 1985 Settlement Agreement (Wax vs. the Town of West
Hartford) for the McAuley SSD development approval. In summary, Mr. Robert Wax agreed to
withdraw his appeal of the development approval in exchange for a number of conditions outlined
in the Settlement Agreement. The proposed 243 Steele Road development has no impact on the
major conditions of the Settlement Agreement which are as follows:
1. Modifications of the McAuley entrance/exit layout including the physical layout of the
pavement, curbs, islands, and pavement marking and signage. This layout was further
revised as part of a recent Town traffic calming project.

page.text: Traffic count and speed data collected by Fuss & O’Neill and the Town of West Hartford indicate
low traffic volumes and vehicle speeds on Stratford Road. The vast majority of traffic traveling
northbound on Steele Road and then proceeding eastbound on Route 44 travels through the
signalized intersection of Route 44 at Steele Road. Only a handful of vehicles proceed up Stratford
Road. Given that the existing background traffic volumes traveling northbound on Steele Road,
and then ultimately east on Route 44, are significantly higher than the volume of proposed
development traffic that will want to travel this same route, the anticipated increase in traffic on
Stratford Road from the proposed development will be negligible.
While traffic count data and analysis does not reveal a significant existing or potential future cut
through traffic issue on Stratford Road that would warrant mitigation, residents have expressed
concern regarding the development’s potential impacts to their roadway. In order to further
minimize or completely eliminate the potential for any cut through traffic on Stratford Road, two
1. Reverse the one-way direction of Stratford Road from north to south (Whetten Road to
Steele Road). This alternative would completely eliminate the potential for cut through
traffic from Steele Road northbound to Route 44 eastbound, however, it could introduce
the potential for cut through traffic in the reverse direction (from Route 44 westbound to
Steele Road southbound). To be implemented, this proposal would require removal of a
portion of the Route 44 median at the north end of Steele Road (south leg of the
2. Close off Stratford Road at the intersection of Whetten Road, install a hammerhead turn
around at the north end, and permit two-way traffic operation. This alternative would
completely eliminate the potential for cut through traffic in either direction on Stratford
Road. However, this option may serve as an inconvenience to some residents along the
northern portion of the roadway who may need to travel more out of the way when
leaving their homes. Should this alternative be pursued, modifications to the curb
extensions at the south end of Stratford Road, along with the removal of a portion of the
north end of the median on Steele Road (south leg of intersection), would be required. In
addition, an emergency access drive or gate should be considered at the north end of
It is our opinion that Option #2 could be safely implemented and would be most effective in
reducing the potential for any cut through traffic. Preliminary review and discussions with the
Town of West Hartford revealed that this option is feasible and could be implemented assuming
support is received from the majority of the Stratford Road residents.

Tighe & Bond has completed a traffic and site plan review of the University’s School for
Young Children (the school) with respect to the proposed residential development across the
street at 243 Steele Road. This memorandum documents the existing traffic conditions
observed along Steele Road during the morning peak hours of the school and reviews the
potential traffic impact of the 243 Steele Road development.
Existing traffic operations at the school were observed during a site visit conducted on
, 2014 from 7:30 AM to 9:30 AM. During the school year, the school
opens at 7:45 AM for the morning extension program with regular hours beginning at 9:00
AM. Traffic operations were observed at the two signalized intersections on either side of
the school, Albany Avenue (Route 44) at Steele Road and Asylum Avenue at Steel Road.
Entering and exiting volumes to the school were recorded from 7:45 AM through 8:45 AM.
During the site visit, the peak along Steele Road for the school was 8:45 AM through 9:05
AM, which is after the morning peak hour for Steel Road, 7:00 AM through 8:00 AM. At
8:50 AM the parking lot had only three vacant spaces and by 9:00 AM it was full. During
this period when the parking lot was full, vehicles were queued waiting to park or vehicles
parked on Steele Road. A maximum queue of three vehicles was observed with three
vehicles parking on Steele Road. The vehicles that parked on-street parked in a seven foot
wide pull-off along the school frontage. By 9:05 AM the parking lot had three open parking
spaces and by 9:10 AM there were no issues finding a parking space. Photographs of the
school driveways and Steele Road taken after the morning peak hour are attached.
It should be noted that the sidewalk adjacent to Steele Road in this area is set back and up
gradient from the on street parked vehicles, requires parents and children to exit their
vehicles along the roadway to the adjacent site driveway to access an appropriately graded
The southern school drive functioned as the entrance and the northern drive as the exit
during the peak, however during the off-peak the southern drive functioned as both an
entrance and exit. When vehicles parked on Steele Road and hand their doors open to
unload children or vehicles were waiting to turn into the school drive traffic driving
northbound on Steele Road would drive in the southbound lane to go around. As long as
the doors were closed of the vehicles parked on Steele Road they did not impact northbound
In addition to the above noted reviews, information has been gathered from the University
and the Children’s School administrator to supplement the limited field information since the
school is now on summer session. Based upon this information, it is reported that there are
frequently queued vehicles on Steele Road in between the school driveways and to the
south of the south driveway. This on-street parking occurs during the drop off of children in
the morning as well as the pickup of the children in the afternoons. The children are
escorted to and from the vehicles given their ages.

Tighe & Bond conducted a review of the Traffic Impact Study completed for 243 Steele Road

There is a concern for the location of the proposed site driveway being in between the two

school, the location the proposed driveway should be directly opposite either of the school
driveways. This is more of a concern with the consideration that there are existing site

While it is fully expected that the traffic study engineer did conduct a field review of the
morning peak hour conditions on Steele Road, it was not noted in the traffic study as it
should be. The traffic engineer should demonstrate the operations of the proposed site
driveway will not impact the existing school peak hour operations.
Based upon the Traffic Study, it is anticipated that this development will generate 102 trips

entering and 45 exiting) during the weekday afternoon peak hour. It is expected that there
will be a 50/50 north-south split for the arrival and departure traffic volumes. While these
trips are based upon ITE trip generation rates and are generally considered appropriate, an
additional similar development traffic generation should be reviewed given the proposed site
location and adjacent uses such as the Children’s School.
